---
import WritingLayout from '../../layouts/WritingLayout.astro';
import { writingPosts } from '../../data/writing';

const post = writingPosts.find(p => p.slug === 'observability-stack')!;
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<WritingLayout post={post}>
  <figure class="my-8 rounded-xl overflow-hidden border border-[#27272A]">
    <img src={`${base}/images/writing/lgtm-stack.svg`} alt="LGTM observability stack diagram" class="w-full" loading="lazy"/>
    <figcaption class="px-4 py-2 bg-[#111115] text-xs text-[#52525B] text-center">The LGTM stack — Loki, Grafana, Tempo, Mimir — correlated in one UI</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>What LGTM Actually Stands For</h2>
  <p>
    LGTM is the Grafana Labs observability stack: <strong>L</strong>oki (logs), <strong>G</strong>rafana
    (visualization), <strong>T</strong>empo (traces), <strong>M</strong>imir (metrics). Some teams
    also add Pyroscope for profiles, making it LGTMP — though nobody calls it that yet.
  </p>
  <p>
    The pitch is a unified query and visualization layer. One Grafana instance. Correlated signals.
    Click from a trace to the logs from that exact span, then to the metrics for that service at that
    timestamp. In practice, getting all of that to work cleanly takes real setup.
  </p>

  <h2>Loki — Logs</h2>
  <p>
    Loki indexes labels, not log content. This is the biggest mental shift coming from Elasticsearch.
    Queries like <code>|= "error"</code> are full-text searches over the raw log stream — fast but
    not indexed. Labels like <code>&#123;namespace="prod", app="api"&#125;</code> are what Loki
    uses to narrow the stream before scanning.
  </p>
  <p>
    Label design matters more than almost anything else. Too many labels = high cardinality = slow
    queries and inflated storage. A good rule: only label what you'd filter on in production. Pod
    name is usually a mistake. Namespace, app, and environment are usually right.
  </p>
  <p>
    For collection, Grafana Alloy (or the older Promtail) runs as a DaemonSet and tails container
    logs from the node. Pipeline stages let you parse JSON logs, extract fields as labels, and drop
    noisy lines before they hit Loki.
  </p>

  <h2>Tempo — Traces</h2>
  <p>
    Tempo is an opinionated trace backend. It doesn't index span attributes — it stores traces by
    trace ID and retrieves them by ID. Search is done via Tempo's TraceQL or by jumping from a
    metric or log that has a trace ID embedded.
  </p>
  <p>
    This means your services need to instrument with OpenTelemetry and propagate trace IDs. For
    Kubernetes workloads, the Grafana Beyla eBPF auto-instrumentation agent can handle this without
    code changes, though with less granularity than manual instrumentation.
  </p>
  <p>
    The killer feature is trace-to-logs correlation. Embed <code>traceID</code> as a structured log
    field, configure Grafana's derived fields to detect it, and you get a one-click link from any
    trace span to the logs from that exact service at that exact time.
  </p>

  <h2>Mimir — Metrics</h2>
  <p>
    Mimir is horizontally scalable Prometheus. If you're running a single Prometheus instance, you
    don't need Mimir. If you have multiple Prometheus instances, long retention requirements, or
    multi-tenant needs, Mimir becomes relevant.
  </p>
  <p>
    Mimir uses the same PromQL you already know. The operational cost is higher — it's a distributed
    system with compactors, ingesters, queriers, and object storage dependencies. For smaller setups,
    Prometheus + Thanos is often a simpler path to long-term storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Grafana — The Glue</h2>
  <p>
    Grafana's value in this stack isn't just dashboards. It's the correlation layer. Configure each
    datasource, then use Grafana's Explore view to jump between signals without pre-building dashboards.
  </p>
  <p>
    Useful configurations that aren't obvious:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Set Loki as a derived field source in Tempo to enable trace → log navigation</li>
    <li>Add exemplars to Prometheus metrics to enable metric → trace navigation</li>
    <li>Use Grafana's provisioning API to version-control all dashboards and datasources as YAML in Git</li>
    <li>Enable Grafana OnCall if you want alerting — it integrates with PagerDuty, Slack, and the rest without needing a separate Alertmanager UI</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When to Use What</h2>
  <p>
    A practical decision table for common questions:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>"Is the service up and healthy?"</strong> → Metrics (Mimir/Prometheus). Uptime, error rate, latency percentiles.</li>
    <li><strong>"What happened during this incident?"</strong> → Logs (Loki). Exact error messages, stack traces, context.</li>
    <li><strong>"Where is the latency coming from?"</strong> → Traces (Tempo). Waterfall view of the request path.</li>
    <li><strong>"Why is CPU/memory high?"</strong> → Profiles (Pyroscope). Flame graphs show which function is burning cycles.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The stack is strongest when signals are correlated. Investing in consistent labeling across all
    four — matching <code>service.name</code>, <code>namespace</code>, and <code>environment</code>
    across every component — is the highest-leverage thing you can do before deploying any of it.
  </p>
</WritingLayout>
